            <creation>This story, with the short title "An Adulterer Condemned But Saved," is recent: the earliest PEMM manuscript* in which this story appears is from around<date>1881</date>.Originally composed in <placeName ref="LOC3010Ethiop">Ethiopia</placeName></creation>
            <abstract>
                <p>There was certain man who, though only a Christian in name, loved Mary and celebrated the feast of her Dormition. However, he was also an adulterer. He was brought to the seat of judgment in heaven, where his deeds were examined. He confessed to his sins, and the people condemned him. The Lord then sentenced him to the fate of adulterers, which involved being fed to an enormous serpent with gnashing teeth. This man cried out to Mary, who stood by the Lord’s side, and he asked for her help. Mary appealed to the Lord on the man’s behalf, and the Lord forgave his sins.</p>
            </abstract>
